{"key":"processedPost-11788453","value":{"id":11788453,"first":11787934,"last":12482530,"when":1262967025,"utime":"01/08/10 06:10 PM","content":"If you have agar, why use a syringe to inoculate the rye?&nbsp; Simply use an agar wedge.&nbsp; <br /><br />It sounds like your filters/lid combination isn't sealing properly.&nbsp; Perhaps you've put the filters on the inside of the lid rather than on the outside?&nbsp; Another common cause of bacterial infection is releasing the pressure after sterilizing rather than waiting for it to return to zero slowly.&nbsp; You also shouldn't remove the jars until they're cool.&nbsp; The old advice to 'remove while hot to shake' is based on using poor technique to prepare the rye.&nbsp; Removing the jars while hot will lead to an increased rate of contamination because they draw in air as they cool and the contents shrink.<br /><br />Also, 99% alcohol doesn't have the killing power of 70%.&nbsp; That's why it's not recommended.<br />RR","title":"Re: Contaminated Rye Every Single Time"}}